SIMPLE: moroseness
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moroseness
<hw>Mo*rose"ness</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Sourness of temper;
sulenness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Learn good humor, never to oppose without just reason; abate some
degrees of pride and <qex>moroseness</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Moroseness</xex> is not precisely
<xex>peevishness</xex> or <xex>fretfulness</xex>, though often
accompanied with it. It denotes more of silence and severity, or
ill-humor, than the irritability or irritation which characterizes
<xex>peevishness</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morosis</ent>⟦br⟧
